    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv (skip error_logs.csv for this step), aggregate by (source_file, cmdb_id, KPI_name) where KPI_name is: for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name. For each group compute: count of points, mean(value), std(value), and global P95 (95th percentile) of value using the full available series (do NOT filter by the incident window). Return a single combined table with these columns: source_file (metric/trace/log), cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, std, p95. Limit the output to the top 50 rows sorted by p95 descending. Also return the total number of distinct cmdb_id and distinct KPI names per source_file (as separate small summary). Do not filter by incident window in this step."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the prior aggregated summary we observed that memory-related metric KPIs dominate the top global P95 values across many components. However, per the diagnosis rules the root-cause component must be chosen from the provided candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). Therefore we should now focus metric-based anomaly detection for only those five candidate services. Using the global thresholds (P95) computed from the full series is required before filtering to the incident window. The next step is to (1) retrieve per-component-per-KPI global P95 (using the full available metric series) for those five services, (2) filter metric.csv to the incident window (2024-01-25 16:45:00 to 2024-01-25 17:15:00 UTC) for those services, and (3) report compact anomaly summaries per component-KPI in the window: number of points, number of anomalies (value >= global P95), earliest anomaly timestamp (if any), max value in window, and the precomputed global P95. This will narrow candidates for downstream trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Restrict to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window when calculating P95). Then filter rows to the incident window: timestamps between 2024-01-25 16:45:00 and 2024-01-25 17:15:00 UTC (use pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) for comparison). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the window return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_in_window, count_anomalies_in_window (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as integer seconds) or null if none, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Limit output rows to at most 20, sorted by count_anomalies_in_window descending then global_p95 descending. Also return the total number of (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups examined (for these five services)."
}

{
    "analysis": "You provided metric-analysis results for the five candidate services and identified multiple anomalous component-KPIs in the incident window. The highest anomaly count is for ts-route-service/socket (3 anomalies), and several services show mem, diskio, cpu, workload, and socket anomalies (mostly 2 points each). According to the workflow, the next step is trace analysis to localize the root-cause component among multiple faulty services (trace data must use global thresholds computed from the full series before filtering to the incident window). Traces can show call relationships and which faulty service is most downstream in faulty call chains. Therefore we should compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace series, then inspect the incident-window trace points that exceed those thresholds for our candidate services to find which services/traces show anomalies and their earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Restrict to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window when calculating P95). Then filter rows to the incident window: timestamps between 2024-01-25 16:45:00 and 2024-01-25 17:15:00 UTC (use pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) for comparison). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the window return: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_in_window, count_anomalies_in_window (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as integer seconds) or null if none, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Limit output rows to at most 20, sorted by count_anomalies_in_window descending then global_p95 descending. Also return the list of distinct trace_name values encountered for these services (limit to top 50 if many)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis narrowed candidates to five services. The strongest metric signal is ts-route-service.socket (3 anomaly points in-window) and multiple services show mem/diskio/cpu/workload spikes (mostly 2 points each). Trace analysis was noisy for error_rate (global P95=0.0 made zeros be counted as anomalies), so trace error_rate is unhelpful as-is; we should focus on non-zero trace metrics if needed later. Given the metrics, ts-route-service.socket stands out as the top anomalous KPI, which points toward a network/socket-related failure. According to the workflow, the next step is log analysis to confirm whether socket/network errors appear in logs (error_logs.csv and log.csv) for ts-route-service and the other candidate services during the incident window. If logs show socket errors or connection failures originating from ts-route-service (and traces show downstream services failing after calls to it), we can localize the root cause and reason (socket error / network).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. Restrict cmdb_id to [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"].\n1) For log.csv: For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute the global P95 using the full available series (do NOT filter by the incident window). Then filter log.csv to the incident window (2024-01-25 16:45:00 to 2024-01-25 17:15:00 UTC). For each (cmdb_id, log_name) in the window return: cmdb_id, log_name, count_in_window, count_anomalies_in_window (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (integer seconds) or null, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Limit rows to top 20 sorted by count_anomalies_in_window desc then global_p95 desc.\n2) For error_logs.csv: filter to the same five cmdb_ids and the incident window. Return: total number of error log entries per cmdb_id, and the top 20 error log rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) sorted by timestamp ascending. Also compute per-cmdb_id counts of messages that contain any of these keywords (case-insensitive): \"socket\", \"timeout\", \"connection\", \"refused\", \"broken\", \"reset\", \"packet\", \"latency\", \"IO\", \"out of memory\", \"OOM\". Return the counts for each keyword per cmdb_id (only include keywords with count>0)."
}

